[This article mentions skinny moose. For a moose to eat certain things
it has to be in poor body condition, or have an acquired taste for a
particular plant. In this case it sounds like these moose were not
getting nearly enough to eat. Consequently hungry animals will eat
things that non-hungry animals will not eat.

The bird cherry (_Prunus padus_) is not native to North America, but
seemed to have originated in northern Europe, including Norway,
Finland, and Sweden, thus the plant is adapted to growing well north
of the Arctic Circle.

The European bird cherry is a different variety than the Chinese bird
cherry, but they are both _Prunus_ spp. All _Prunus_ spp are regarded
as being toxic because of their ability to produce prussic acid.

Prussic acid, hydrocyanic acid, and hydrogen cyanide are all terms
relating to cyanide poisoning. The _Prunus_ spp of plants and other
common plants may accumulate large quantities of cyanogenic
glycosides, (a sugar compound with cyanide attached) which are located
in the outer tissue or epidermal layer of the plant.

An enzyme resides in the inner or mesophyll leaf tissues. When an
event stresses the plant, such as frost, drought, drought followed by
rain and a sudden burst of growth, or trauma to the plant, the
mesophyll portion of the plant or leaf releases the enzyme, which
breaks down the cyanogenic glycosides releasing the cyanide compound
and the sugar. The sugar makes the plant tasty and cyanide makes the
plant deadly.

Japanese yew (_Taxus cuspidate_) produces taxane, a cardioactive
compound. This plant is eaten by curious animals, and by those that
are very hungry.

With both toxic plants in one animal it would be difficult to say
which toxic agent was responsible for the animal's demise.

However, with plant parts of the bird cherry in several animals, this
is evidence these animals are likely hungry, and eating this plant.
This plant has likely experienced some growth in the 40 deg F (4.4 deg
C) weather and then a cold blast of weather stressed it, thus
releasing the cyanide compounds.

Photos of the bird cherry may be found at
<http://photo.net/photodb/photo?photo_id=9413714> and
<http://www.naturephoto-cz.com/european-bird-cherry:prunus-padus-photo-11387.html>

Photos of the Japanese yew may be found at
<http://home.howstuffworks.com/japanese-yew.htm> and
<http://foragingpictures.com/plants/Japanese_yew/h0002.htm>. - Mod.TG

